{
 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a4a9e3e6-b2f7-46fb-8730-8a5a96fa0594",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Iterators and Iterables - Lecture"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "519be241-1330-4754-ae42-e5f7088f65fe",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Iterators\n",
    "\n",
    "We saw that an iterator is an object that implements\n",
    "__iter__ -> returns object itself\n",
    "__next__ -> returns next element\n",
    "\n",
    "The drawback is that iterators get exhausted\n",
    "-> become useless for iterating again\n",
    "-> become throw away objects\n",
    "\n",
    "But two distinct things going on:\n",
    "- maintaining the collection of objects (container) (e.g. creating, mutating, etc..)\n",
    "- iterating over collection\n",
    "\n",
    "Why should we have to re-create the collection of items just to iterate over them?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "92e7e2af-b85c-4fc9-b8a2-8ba7fe6d4b4f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Separating the Collection from the Iterator\n",
    "\n",
    "Instead we would prefer to separate these two\n",
    "- Maintaining the data of collection should be one object\n",
    "- Iterating over data should be a separate object -> iterator\n",
    "- That object is thrown-away -> but we don't throw away the collection\n",
    "\n",
    "The collection is iterable\n",
    "But the iterator is responsible for iterating over the collection\n",
    "\n",
    "The iterable is created once\n",
    "The iterator is created every time we need to start a fresh iteration"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "4c515944-a286-4bf0-8cd3-795fb341a437",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Example\n",
    "\n",
    "class Cities:\n",
    "    def __init__(self):\n",
    "        self._cities = ['Paris', 'Berlin', 'Rome', 'London']\n",
    "        self._index = 0\n",
    "\n",
    "    def __iter__(self):\n",
    "        return self\n",
    "\n",
    "    def __next__(self):\n",
    "        if self._index >= len(self._cities):\n",
    "            raise StopIteration\n",
    "        else:\n",
    "            item = self._cities[self._index]\n",
    "            self._index += 1\n",
    "            return item\n",
    "\n",
    "Cities instances are iterators\n",
    "Every time we want to run a new loop, we have to create a new instance of Cities\n",
    "This is wasteful because we should not have to re-create the _cities list every time"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "6e9b36fe-231f-489a-8b08-e742585238b9",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Example\n",
    "\n",
    "So lets separate the object that maintains the cities from the iterator itself\n",
    "\n",
    "class Cities:\n",
    "    def __init__(self):\n",
    "        self._cities = ['Paris', 'Berlin', 'Rome', 'London']\n",
    "        self._index = 0\n",
    "\n",
    "    def __len__(self):\n",
    "        return len(self._cities)\n",
    "\n",
    "class CityIterator:\n",
    "    def __init__(self, cities):\n",
    "        self._cities = cities\n",
    "        self._index = 0\n",
    "\n",
    "    def __iter__(self):\n",
    "        return self\n",
    "\n",
    "    def __next__(self):\n",
    "        if self._index >= len(self._cities):\n",
    "            raise StopIteration\n",
    "        else:\n",
    "            item = self._cities[self._index]\n",
    "            self._index += 1\n",
    "            return item"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "dce92ec2-d120-4106-a779-837ba6536ffa",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Example\n",
    "\n",
    "To use Cities and CityIterator together here's how we would proceed:\n",
    "\n",
    "cities = Cities()\n",
    "city_iterator = CityIterator(cities)\n",
    "\n",
    "for city in cities_iterator:\n",
    "    print(city)\n",
    "\n",
    "At this point cities_iterator is exhausted\n",
    "If we want to re-iterate over collection we need to create a new one\n",
    "\n",
    "city_iterator = CityIterator(cities)\n",
    "for city in cities_iterator:\n",
    "    print(city)\n",
    "\n",
    "But this time we did not have to re-create the collection we just passed in the existing one!"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "85836f28-2348-46a2-b562-05cecf45cb25",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "So far...\n",
    "\n",
    "At this point we have:\n",
    "- a container that maintains the collection item\n",
    "- a separate object, the iterator, used to iterate over the collection\n",
    "\n",
    "So we can iterate over collection as many times as we want\n",
    "- we just have to remember toe create a new iterator every time\n",
    "\n",
    "It would be nice if we didn't have to do that and we could just iterate over Cities instead of CityIterator\n",
    "\n",
    "This is where the formal definition of Python iterable comes in.."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "578b76ba-0794-43c5-b8f3-1296e5784d02",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Iterable\n",
    "\n",
    "An iterable is a Python object that implements the iterable protocol\n",
    "The iterable protocol requires that the object implement a single method\n",
    "\n",
    "__iter__ returns a new instance of the iterator object used to iterate over the iterable\n",
    "\n",
    "class Cities:\n",
    "    def __init__(self):\n",
    "        self._cities = ['Paris', 'Berlin', 'Rome', 'London']\n",
    "        self._index = 0\n",
    "\n",
    "    def __len__(self):\n",
    "        return len(self._cities)\n",
    "\n",
    "    def __iter__(self):\n",
    "        return CityIterator(self)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "8a04913d-bdc5-4ef2-ba93-5172c3401612",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Iterable vs Iterator\n",
    "\n",
    "An iterable is an object tha implements \n",
    "__iter__ -> returns an iterator (in general a new instance)\n",
    "\n",
    "An iterator is an object that implements\n",
    "__iter__ -> returns itself (an iterator) (not a new instance)\n",
    "__next__ -> returns the next element\n",
    "\n",
    "So iterators are themselves iterables but are iterables that become exhausted\n",
    "Iterables on the other hand never become exhausted because they always return a new iterator that is used to iterate"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "8129ab85-5351-49e9-a886-875bbd658738",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Iterating over an iterable\n",
    "\n",
    "Python has a built-in function iter()\n",
    "It calls the __iter__ method (come back to this)\n",
    "\n",
    "The first thing Python does when we try an iterable over an object\n",
    "It calls the iter() to obatin an iterator\n",
    "Then it starts iterating (using next, StopIteration, etc..) using the iterator returned by iter()"
   ]
  },
